{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489766"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"739"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/739"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.03,0.15,0.12,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"},{"type":"tags","id":"8331"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of intermittent pain and swelling on the left side of his face. The swelling appears when he is eating and then settles after a few hours. His appetite has decreased over the last few months and he has lost 5 kg in weight. He has a medical history of hypertension and carcinoma of the stomach. He underwent a gastrectomy 12 months ago. He does not take any regular medications. He has a 36 pack-year smoking history and works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is a palpable firm lump beneath the left side of the mandible (Image). The lump is not tender or mobile. There are no other palpable lumps in the neck. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound","Orthopantomogram","CT with contrast","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Sialogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of sialolithiasis (salivary gland stone), which is the most common disease of salivary glands. The intermittent swelling in the submandibular area that occurs with eating is characteristic of a stone in Wharton\u0027s duct. However, the patient\u0027s history of weight loss, decreased appetite, smoking history, and previous cancer also raise concerns about potential malignancy. Even though the diagnosis would fit well for a salivary duct stone, a recurrence of his known malignancy must be excluded first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation in this case. It can detect both salivary stones and evaluate for potential malignancy. CT can reveal features such as calculi, necrotic nodes, or primary tumors, providing a comprehensive assessment of the submandibular region and surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful, non-invasive method for examining salivary glands and can detect stones and masses. However, given the concern for potential malignancy in this case, CT would provide more detailed information about both the gland and surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrthopantomogram\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-ray that can diagnose sialoliths but provides limited information about soft tissues and would not be adequate to evaluate for potential malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that can provide a tissue sample for diagnosis. While it can be useful when there\u0027s a strong suspicion of malignancy, it\u0027s not typically the first-line investigation, especially when sialolithiasis is also suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialogram\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive test that can identify the presence and location of a stone in the salivary gland duct. While it\u0027s excellent for diagnosing sialolithiasis, it doesn\u0027t provide adequate information about potential malignancy, which is a concern in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all these investigations have their place in the evaluation of salivary gland pathology, CT with contrast provides the most comprehensive initial assessment given this patient\u0027s presentation and risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sialolithiasis is the most common disease of salivary glands, accounting for approximately 50% of all major salivary gland pathology.","CT with contrast is the preferred initial investigation when there is suspicion of both sialolithiasis and potential malignancy."],"references":["Kraaij S, Karagozoglu KH, Forouzanfar T, Veerman EC, Brand HS. Salivary stones: symptoms, aetiology, biochemical composition and treatment. Br Dent J. 2014 Dec 5;217(11):E23. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25476659/","J\u00e4ger L, Menauer F, Holzknecht N, Scholz V, Grevers G, Reiser M. Sialolithiasis: MR sialography of the submandibular duct--an alternative to conventional sialography and US? Radiology. 2000 Sep;216(3):665-71. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10966693/","Demidov V,  Khrulenko S. Sialoliths of Submandibular Gland and Wharton\u2019s Duct: Orthopantomography. J Diagn Treat Oral Maxillofac Pathol 2021;5(7):77\u201386. Available at: https://dtjournal.org/articles/187"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20042"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20042"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/15249b10-75c2-4473-999c-783ca76cebe2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/15249b10-75c2-4473-999c-783ca76cebe2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91493"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-18T10:27:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-18T10:28:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t